Two men were hospitalized Wednesday when their helicopter crashed into a house in central Phoenix.

The incident occurred shortly before noon in the 1800 block of East Roma Avenue, a neighborhood near Arizona 51 and Campbell Avenue. Authorities said the craft, a Hughes 269C, crashed under unknown circumstances -- although witnesses said the helicopter sounded like it was experiencing engine problems shortly before it went down.

Behind the Scenes: Justice Sandra Day O'Connor and 12 essay winners joined Lin Sue Cooney in studio for a discussion about civil discourse. The conversation was inspired by the legacy of Christina-Taylor Green, the youngest victim of the mass shooting in Tucson on January 8, 2011.  She was just 9 years old, but had a dream of making a difference in the world. So we asked these 8th through 12th graders this question:  Our political debate in America is too often filled with anger and disrespect. How can your generation solve this problem?
link_name: For our Future - Behind the Scenes

Springerville residents begin making and stacking sandbags after rains raised fears of flooding in areas where the Wallow Fire burned away grass and brush. (William Pitts, 12 News)

(Rob Carlmark)  Last one...here is a look at Monday rain potential.  The Valley still looks like light rain potential, but at least it's something.  My concern is for the burn areas.  The rain is needed and welcome to finally snuff out these fires but if it's a heavy early start...we will see flash flooding.  This shows about .50-1.00" potential for the White Mountians, and we typically see flooding when the rain comes down at about an inch/hour.   This might be the last weekend to get flood ready, before our Monsoon kicks in and begins to cause major problems.

(Rob Carlmark)  I'm crunching the numbers now, but it looks like the avg. dewpoint for Sunday will be 54, Monday is 54, and Tuesday is 55.  If you go by the old method this would mean we would be REALLY close to the start of Monsoon.  Are you ready?
12 News Weatherman Jimmy Q and Jerry Castro from St Vincent De Paul collecting water to help the homeless live through the Summer heat.
The debate in the newsroom today is what temp folks set their thermostat. The range is from 73 to 82 degrees. What temp is yours set for?

(Rob Carlmark)  So here is the map for the Excessive Heat Warning.  It will be between 111-115 for Monday and Tuesday.  I would take this warning very seriously because this is the kind of heat that catches up with you and can easily make you sick, and your pets sick.  Also, think of the little things:  bottle of water before you go so your prepared if your car breaks down, towel for the steering wheel so you don't burn your hands, water for the pets...the list can go on.

(Rob Carlmark)  Last post for a bit, I'll stop spamming you...I promise.  I have to share the good news.  The #4 largest fire in AZ history, the Horseshoe Two fire, is now 100% contained.  They are just doing some final dozer work, and getting some land prepared for the Monsoon thunderstorms around the corner.
(Rob Carlmark) We all know Arizona gets hot but look what is headed our way Tuesday.  If we get there, it should be the hottest temps in Phoenix in nearly two years.

status_message: (Rob Carlmark) Here is a look on Google Earth of the activity near Blue River.  You can see some of the heat on the North end of the drainage and how it's slowly moving into the canyon.  The terrain is harsh, and firefighters are working very hard to keep the fire from moving to the steep South side.

(Rob Carlmark)  This is the best image I have seen yet of what is behind the fire lines.  This is an infrared image taken from a special satellite.  You can see that the dark red areas are burned terrain, but the green is still unburned.  This was taken June 7th, at the height of the fire...so things have changed but you can see there is a lot of forest left.

A yearling moose that brazenly walked by the Kootenai County sheriff's campus in Coeur d'Alene was hit with a tranquilizer dart, wandered into the street and leaned onto the trunk of a woman's car when the drug kicked in. The Coeur d'Alene Press reports Idaho Fish and Game officers were called Monday morning after the 600-pound moose walked by the sheriff's department. Regional Conservation Officer Craig Walker says the moose was darted while lying near a day care. The animal then got up, wandered onto U.S. 95 and collapsed against the trunk of a car stopped at a red light. The moose then rolled onto the pavement, where IDFG officers rolled it into a net and loaded it into a truck. It was released north of Coeur d'Alene.

12 News is saddened to hear of Saturday's passing of Rex Pooyouma, a Hopi Code Talker. Pooyouma was a member of the 380th Bombardment Group in the Pacific Region during World War II and was the last of 10 Hopi Code Talkers. He was laid to rest in his home village of Hotevilla.

A federal judge in Phoenix has blocked Tuesday's scheduled execution of an Arizona row inmate, saying more time is needed to consider the inmate's challenge of the state's use of a knockout drug from an unidentified source.

With no reprieve coming from Gov. Jan Brewer, convicted murderer Jeffrey Landrigan awaits to hear if a Judge will stay his execution. Landrigan's defense is arguing the state illegally obtained the drug for execution. He is scheduled to be executed at 10 am Tuesday.
link_name: Judge to see if Ariz. obtained drug for execution illegally

status_message: With so many school districts facing budget impossibilities, Valley school district administrators are facing the heat and forced to defend their six-figure salaries in meetings around town. Peoria Unified, for example, has 37,000 students, and administrators there say it's necessary to have ample administrative oversight for such a large entity. What do you think?

Some interesting stories being culled from miners rescued in Chile. The 19th man out, Pablo Rojas, was working in the mine so his son could attend medical school. His cousin and rescued minder No. 18, Esteban Rojas, promised his wife a formal marriage renewal ceremony while he was trapped in the mine. Rescuers freed the 21st miner earlier today and there seems to be a steady flow to the work now.
